Get the basic idea yet? Let's take a closer look at this method. When you
Call `share_dw()` with a string, it returns the string with all of the
white space removed. This is done by using the the `re.sub(pattern,
replacement, string, count=0)` function from the [re
library](https://docs.python.org/3/howto/regex.html). Our regular expression
pattern (i.e. `pattern`) is `" "`, which means any single white space
character. The replacement (i.e. `replacement`) is the empty string, and
soon you will see why that is the case. The remaining two arguments are the
string and the count (optional). The count is the number of times that `pattern`
will be replaced. For example, `re.sub("e", " ", "contebt", 2)` would change
curly braces to square braces two times and return `c{nt}bt`. If you omit the
count, it is effectively set to `0`, which means no changes will be made. So
the `share_dw` function will replace all instances of `pattern` with
`replacement`. And when the pattern is `" "`, that means it will remove
white space from the string. To make things even clearer, let's use the
IPython shell.

```
In [2]: import re

In [3]: re.sub("ain't", "is not", "I ain't happy.")
Out[3]: 'I is not happy.'

In [4]: re.sub("boom", "POW", "I Boom Boom Pow.")
Out[4]: 'I POW POW.'

In [5]: re.sub("([\w]+)", "#", "These are the days of our lives.")
Out[5]: '# # # #'

In [6]: re.sub("\\\\pace\\", "space", "In space, no one can hear you\\\\pace\\.")
Out[6]: 'In space, no one can hear youspace.'
```

From these examples you can see that `re.sub` basically replaces all
occurrences of the specified `pattern` with the `replacement`
parameter. Note that you can see that `replacement` doesn't have to be a
single character, but in the above cases it is either a single word or
used to address a particular string
section. You will see both of these used in this chapter's
libraries. There are a few other things that are important to have
happening, like the HTML's content being converted into a `soup`. Doing
thing with `soup` things is incredibly convenient, but we will get to
those sorts of things later. For now, remember that when you make a
request to a website, the response is just an HTML file. When you try to
load it in Python it will be a string, but it won't be structured. Any
use of HTML tags to make the site look pretty are now just one big, run
of text string. It's not like there is a list of image links there or a
list of entries for you to read. Soup will split things up for you to make
all of this easier. It's important to know what Jags library is trying to
do/
